ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="grid grid-rows-[auto_auto] min-w-0"><div class="row-start-1 col-start-1 min-w-0"><div class="min-w-0 pl-2 py-1.5"><div class="flex items-center gap-2"><button class="group/status flex items-center gap-2 py-1 text-sm transition-colors cursor-pointer text-left text-text-500 hover:text-text-300 flex-1 min-w-0" aria-expanded="false"><div class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 min-w-0" style="opacity: 1;"><span class="truncate text-sm font-base">Brainstormed practical strategies for LinkedIn visibility</span><span class="inline-flex transition-transform duration-200 shrink-0 -rotate-90"><div style="width: 12px; height: 12px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;"><svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-hidden="true" style="flex-shrink: 0;"><path d="M14.128 7.165a.502.502 0 0 1 .744.67l-4.5 5-.078.07a.5.5 0 0 1-.666-.07l-4.5-5-.06-.082a.501.501 0 0 1 .729-.656l.075.068L10 11.752z"></path></svg></div></span></div></button></div><span class="sr-only" role="status" aria-live="polite">Brainstormed practical strategies for LinkedIn visibility</span><div class="grid transition-[grid-template-rows] duration-300 ease-out" style="grid-template-rows: 0fr;"><div class="overflow-hidden min-w-0"></div></div></div></div><div class="row-start-2 col-start-1 relative grid isolate min-w-0"><div class="row-start-1 col-start-1 relative z-[2] min-w-0"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Good practical question. Here are your realistic options:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Option 1: Write a LinkedIn article or post documenting the build</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">This is the most common approach. You write a post or long-form article that covers:</p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">The problem you set out to solve</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">How you designed the agent (screenshots of the system prompt, the knowledge base structure)</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">A short screen recording of it working</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">What you learned</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">No certificate needed. The artifact is the post itself.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Option 2: Upload a PDF case study to your profile</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">LinkedIn lets you add media to your experience section. A well-structured PDF case study attached to your Scorewarrior role is more credible than a badge.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Option 3: GitHub + link it from LinkedIn</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Even if you don't code, you can create a GitHub repository with:</p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">A README explaining the agent design</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Your system prompt</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Sample test conversations</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Documentation of the logic</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Then link that repo in your LinkedIn featured section. It signals technical literacy without requiring deep engineering.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Option 4: Record a short demo video</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">A 2-3 minute Loom video showing the agent handling a realistic customer support scenario, with you narrating the design decisions. Post it on LinkedIn natively (LinkedIn favors video reach). This gets attention and demonstrates actual capability.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The honest reality</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Any of these outperforms a course certificate because they show output, not just consumption. Recruiters and hiring managers in your space are more likely to engage with "I built this and here's how it works" than "I completed a course."</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Which of these feels most achievable given your current bandwidth?</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
